Date:8/11/2011 1:14:31 PM
From:E_K_S
I assume that as you pay down your debt, BV increases by the same amount since
your liabilities are being reduced. Share amount stays the same but liabilities
go down. In SVU's case that's $550M. They have 212M shares so that's an
increase in value by $2.29/share.

It's similar to paying off a mortgage over thirty years. When you make the last
payment you own the home free and clear. I am assuming that SVU is paying down
principle so it's possible that the amount they state in their 10K also
includes interest then the actual debt payed down would be less. In either case
it is large (relative to the shares outstanding).

What is encouraging is their new CEO has been very consistent in paying down
their enormous debt incurred from the Albertson's acquisition done 6/2006.
Since his tenure, he has already whittle down $1B of the $7B in debt at close
to $500M/year.

What's your take? Many here have stated that SUV is a value trap. I think the
company will be 50% higher rather than 50% lower from the current market price
of $7.20/share.

